<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">ever saw, and intersected by little Runs of water at every three or four miles until you come to the last and largest called Methcoutisaque River, where a small band of Indi<span class="DelHand-author">a</span><span class="AddHand-author">e</span>ns have their gardens and where about half a mile up the creek there is a Capital fall for a mile.  The distance from S<sup>t</sup> Marys to Fort S<sup>t</sup> Joseph is thirteen computed leagues and from thence to Michilimackinac fifteen<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The north side of the River opposite the Village is generally a rocky Swamp but as the ground gradually Rises, the soil improves and is covered with Maple &amp;<sup>c</sup> until it terminates about six miles back in a Ridge of Rocky mountain which encircles the whole northern Shore of Lake Superior.  On this side about three leagues before the Fall there is a small but Rappid River called garden River which takes its Rise in the mountains above mentioned: a short distance from its mouth it is impracticable to Canoes, becoming a mere Torrent obstructed with Trees and Rocks, it is however remarkable for having about three leagues from the entrance a Steep and perpendicular Clay bank at the bottom of which are found a great variety of pet<span class="AddHand-author">ri</span>factions.  These Mountains are thought</p>

